Water Quality in North Carolina: Nutrients and Specific Conductance

Peggy Chen

2024-06-28

R Markdown

Using the USGS dataRetrieval package to plot the frequency of measuring certain chemicals across North Carolina.

Paramter codes, or PCodes, are dependent on the chemical or physical factor being tested. For a list of the codes, go to: https://help.waterdata.usgs.gov/code/parameter_cd_query?fmt=rdb&group_cd=NUT&inline=true

Need help? Type into the console: HASP::explore_site()

Plotting total nitrogen testing sites across NC

Note that total nitrogen in this plot is defined as nitrate, nitrite, ammonia, organic-N, and is tested in water, unfiltered, and measured in milligrams per liter.

# What sites measured nitrogen in North Carolina? 
nitrogen_sites <- whatNWISsites(stateCd = "NC", 
                          parameterCd = "00600")
nrow(nitrogen_sites)
## [1] 795
# Identify these sites 
names(nitrogen_sites)
## [1] "agency_cd"   "site_no"     "station_nm"  "site_tp_cd"  "dec_lat_va" 
## [6] "dec_long_va" "colocated"   "queryTime"
# Plot the locations of these sites 
usa <- st_as_sf(maps::map("state", fill=TRUE, plot =FALSE),
                crs = 4269)

sf_nitrogen <- st_as_sf(nitrogen_sites, 
                  coords = c("dec_long_va", "dec_lat_va"),
                  crs = 4269)

# Bad map :( 
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = usa[ usa$ID == "north carolina" ,]) +
  geom_sf(data = sf_nitrogen) + 
  xlab(NULL)+
  ylab(NULL)+
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) + 
  labs(title = "USGS Locations that Meausure Total Nitrogen in Water across North Carolina", 
       caption = "Laura DeCicco, USGS. 2021")

Filtered Data Example

This example filters the points so that rather than displaying all locations where nitrogen is tested, it only finds sites with more than 100 measurements and at least 5 measurements per year

# Assign codes and pull data 
pCode <- c("00600")
phNC <- whatNWISdata(stateCd="NC", 
                     parameterCd=pCode)
## WARNING: Beginning in mid-March 2024, NWIS will not deliver
## new discrete water quality data or updates to existing data. 
## For updated information visit: https://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/qwdata
## For additional details, see:
## https://doi-usgs.github.io/dataRetrieval/articles/Status.html
## https://doi-usgs.github.io/dataRetrieval/articles/qwdata_changes.html
## If you have additional questions about the qw data service,
## email CompTools@usgs.gov.
# Filter data acc. to freq and measurement count 
phNC_1 <- phNC %>% 
  filter(count_nu > 100) %>% # At least 100 measurments 
  mutate(period = as.Date(end_date) - as.Date(begin_date)) %>%
  filter(period > 5*365) # At least 5x/year 

nitrogen_NC_data <- readNWISqw(siteNumbers = phNC_1$site_no,
                         parameterCd = pCode)
## Warning in readNWISqw(siteNumbers = phNC_1$site_no, parameterCd = pCode): WARNING: Beginning in mid-March 2024, NWIS will not deliver
## new discrete water quality data or updates to existing data. 
## For updated information visit: https://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/qwdata
## For additional details, see:
## https://doi-usgs.github.io/dataRetrieval/articles/Status.html
## https://doi-usgs.github.io/dataRetrieval/articles/qwdata_changes.html
## If you have additional questions about the qw data service,
## email CompTools@usgs.gov.
# Lets look at the maximum measured value, and number of samples 
nitrogen_summary <- nitrogen_NC_data %>% 
  group_by(site_no) %>% 
  summarize(max = max(result_va, na.rm = TRUE),
            count = n()) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  left_join(attr(nitrogen_NC_data, "siteInfo"), 
            by = "site_no")

# Prep data to map >:( 
sf_nitrogen <- st_as_sf(nitrogen_summary, 
                       coords = c("dec_long_va", "dec_lat_va"),
                       crs = 4269)

# Map 
plot_1 <- ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = usa[ usa$ID == "north carolina" ,]) +
  geom_sf(data = sf_nitrogen) + 
  xlab(NULL)+
  ylab(NULL)+
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) + 
  labs(title = "Nitrogen in North Carolina", 
       caption = "Laura DeCicco, USGS. 2021") 
plot_1

Plotting over time

These plots are measurements of specific conductance overtime, and the site codes are obtained from the sf_conductivity data that can be found in the environment.

site <- "02129000"

qw_data <- readWQPqw(paste0("USGS-", site),
                     c("Specific conductance"))
## NEWS: USGS data availability and format are changing. 
## Beginning in mid-March 2024 the data obtained from legacy profiles
## will not include new USGS data or recent updates to existing data. 
## To view the status of changes in data availability and code functionality, visit:
## https://doi-usgs.github.io/dataRetrieval/articles/Status.html
## If you have additional questions about these changes, 
## email CompTools@usgs.gov.
plot <- ggplot(data = qw_data, aes(x = ActivityStartDate, y = ResultMeasureValue)) + 
  geom_point()
plot
